messages.content: 9-1-1, what's your emergency?
I just got back from work from Target. I'm at 338 Thompson Drive, and I found my fiancée on the floor in the kitchen. There's blood everywhere.
Okay, listen to me. Stay on the phone. You said there's blood everywhere? Is she conscious?
No, she's not. Please help.
Okay, I need you to take a deep breath, okay? Is she conscious right now?
No, she's cold. I don't understand what's happening.
Listen to me, you need to calm down, okay? We're going to get through this. How old is she?
She just turned 59 years old.
Alright. And you said she's not awake?
I don't want to touch anything, but there's blood.
Can you check if she's awake?
I don't know. When I got here, the front door was unlocked.
I understand. I need you to answer this right now. Is she awake?
No, she's not breathing.
She's not breathing either?
No.
Okay. And you said the door was open?
No, it was unlocked. It's unusual for it to be unlocked.
Have you been through the whole house yet?
No, ma'am.
Okay, I want you to leave the house. Are you sure she's not breathing?
She's not breathing. Please, God, get somebody here.
I have them coming, okay? But if you've not searched the whole house, I need you to go back outside and wait by your car. Do you understand?
Yes.
What do you mean about the blood?
When I came in, I walked into the kitchen where I put my keys. I saw her on the floor. I fell over, and she's cold.
Do you think she's beyond help?
Yes. Please get an ambulance.
I have them coming, okay? But I'm worried about your safety right now. You said the front door was unlocked?
Yes, it's unusual.
Okay, give me a second. What time did you leave the house?
Around 9:45. I left to get something to eat before going to work.
And you found her on the floor where?
In the kitchen, close to the dining area. My God, who would do this?
When was the last time you spoke to her?
Right before I left. We said goodbye, she gave me a kiss, and I drove off.
I have EMS and the fire department coming out there.
She had both outside lights on; that's unusual for her.
The lights were on when you arrived?
Yes, I thought she might have gone to sleep and forgot to lock the door.
Are you outside right now?
Yes, I'm in the driveway. Please tell them to hurry.
They are on the way. I'm not going to get off the phone with you. Stay with me.
Okay.
Who could have done this to her?
Did you touch her at all?
I felt her with the back of my hand. She's cold.
Do you think you're safe where you are right now?
Yes, I'm fine. I don't know if she fell, but there's blood. There's a towel around her ankles, and there's blood at her head.
She was going to stay up until midnight to ring her grandmother's bell for the 4th of July, so I know she would have been awake.
They're coming, okay? Stay put.
The EMS team is here.
